1. '''To stoop or descend'''; to let one's self down; to submit; to waive the privilege of rank or dignity; to accommodate one's self to an inferior. 
Eg. a.``Condescend to men of low estate.'' --Rom. xii. 16.

b.Can they think me so broken, so debased With corporal servitude, that my mind ever Will condescend to such absurd commands? --Milton.

c.Spain's mighty monarch, In gracious clemency, does condescend, On these conditions, to become your friend. --Dryden.

Note: Often used ironically, implying an assumption of superiority.

d.Those who thought they were honoring me by condescending to address a few words to me. --F. W. Robinson.


2. '''To consent'''. [Obs.]

All parties willingly condescended heruento. --R. Carew.

Syn: To yield; stoop; descend; deign; vouchsafe.